    <sec sec-type="intro" id="s1">
      <title>INTRODUCTION</title>
      <p>The roots of the Flow Cytometry Research Facility (FCRF) at University of Nebraska Medical Center (UNMC) reach back to 1980 when 1 research technician became the sole operator for a new technology located in an individual investigator&#x02019;s laboratory. At that time, flow cytometry technology was very complicated and offered researchers new, powerful analysis techniques that were not common practice. As with many novel and complicated technologies, the technician became the resident expert within the laboratory, as well as the point of contact for the few collaborating investigators. As demand for flow cytometry technology increased at the institute, the resident expert secured cytometry technology independent of an individual investigator&#x02019;s laboratory and created a core service. Over the following 25 yr, the core updated and increased the technology offered from 1 flow cytometer to 9 and increased access to the technology, from serving 1 to 3 laboratories in the mid-1980s to &#x0003e;85 independent laboratories in 2010. In financial yr 2010 (July 1, 2009&#x02013;June 30, 2010), the total use of service at the facility was &#x0003e;5000 h. Core personnel and management structure grew, along with the increased use, and by 2004, the staff included 3 full-time employees (FTEs): a core staff member reporting to the core manager and the manager reporting to the core director.</p>
      <p>As flow cytometry technology became easier to operate but increasingly complex in capabilities, <italic>e.g.</italic>, more lasers, increased dimensions acquired, and greater reagent availability, the need for interaction and collaboration to use this technology effectively grew. To highlight this development in core facilities, Moore and Roederer<xref rid="B1" ref-type="bibr">
          <sup>1</sup>
        </xref> published best practices for Shared Resource Laboratories (SRLs), focusing on flow cytometry technology. The authors outline key performance aspects crucial to operating an effective SRL. These include the following: a highly qualified and active core director; knowledgeable and service-oriented staff; high-quality, cost-effective service; education as part of the SRL mission; and maintenance of high-quality, state-of-the-art instrumentation, an active research and development program, a knowledgeable and involved scientific advisory board, high-quality space, fiscally sound budget, and shared institutional responsibilities. The focal point is that SRLs no longer simply provide a service but are key partners for biomedical research laboratories in effective flow cytometry experiments. The aforementioned characteristics are indicators of how SRLs can achieve this partner status.
      </p>
      <p>Many SRLs have education as a fundamental practice, where they teach end users the basic concepts of the technology and applications and train individuals to operate instrumentation. This is an effective use of core instrumentation and resource scientist expertise (we differentiate a resource scientist from a research technologist, where a resource scientist is highly skilled in a technology-focused and service-oriented position, such as a flow cytometry SRL). These fundamental SRL performance aspects provide a roadmap for SRLs to tweak operations and align themselves with standard best practices.</p>
      <p>At the FCRF, there were compounding problems. First, the manner in which the service was offered had not been updated since the mid-1980s. Through a concierge interface, end users would deliver samples to the core, fill in an information sheet denoting the experimental essentials (including fluorescent reagents used and sample type), and expect core staff to acquire and analyze the data autonomously. There was little-to-no interaction on the biology and minimal follow-up on the experiment or analyses. Second, education was not a part of the mission at the FCRF; end users of this core deemed flow cytometry to be fee for service with minimal interaction. Finally, with increasing FCRF work hours putting strain on operations, there were personnel losses: the core manager moved to a new position outside of the FCRF, and the director was retiring. By 2013, this left 1 core personnel to operate 9 instruments, acquiring and analyzing data for &#x0003e;85 independent laboratories. Data quality was decreasing, complaints to the Office of the Vice Chancellor for Research (VCR) about core operations at the FCRF were becoming more frequent, and use appeared to have exceeded capacity for 1 individual and 9 instruments. In October 2013, a new strategic direction was deemed necessary to tackle 2 key gaps in operation at the FCRF: 1) support UNMC faculty needs that were not being met by the facility, and 2) modify facility operations to increase staff recruitment potential, investigator interaction, and use.</p>
      <p>To achieve this necessary change, we adapted concepts from a product lifecycle management approach. Product lifecycle management is a concept from manufacturing and commonly applied in information technology. Stark<xref rid="B2" ref-type="bibr">
          <sup>2</sup>
        </xref> defines product lifecycle management as an effective way that a product can be overseen from initial ideas to retirement, the objective being to increase the value of current and future products for the customer and shareholders. The 5 phases of product lifecycle management are the following: 1) idea, 2) definition, 3) realization, 4) maintenance, and 5) disposal. The product that we define here is not a material article but a process for SRLs to become key partners for biomedical research. The goal of a product management lifecycle approach was identical to that of the SRL: increase the value of the current SRL for customers and stakeholders and continue developing this in the future. We modified the phases of the conventional product lifecycle management approach to achieve the shared goals and to address the different type of product, and we had no intention of disposing of or retiring the SRL. From this, 4 phases were defined: 1) conception, 2) design, 3) implementation, and 4) continued management.
      </p>
      <p>For phase 1, what we wanted to achieve had to be identified. Once this was identified, we started phase 2, the design&#x02014;developing the plan for achieving this change in operation. We took a top-down approach, focusing on functional requirements of the core, and this guided how we would achieve the end goal. Phase 3&#x02014;implementation&#x02014;is where the plan was put into action. Finally, phase 4&#x02014;continued management&#x02014;was where we monitored the response to the change and took corrective steps to fulfill the needs of the SRL to the institution.</p>
      <p>A multifaceted approach (including literature review, personal communication, assessing peer institutions, and surveying the end user needs locally at UNMC) was taken to determine what the end goal would be. The benefits of independent end-user acquisition of flow cytometry data are well defined<xref rid="B1" ref-type="bibr">
          <sup>1</sup>
        </xref> and appeared to be appropriate to implement at the FCRF. The updating of the structure of services to allow for this independent acquisition was approached in Phases 2&#x02013;4 of this product lifecycle management.
      </p>
      <p>Furthermore, a new director was hired at the end of 2013, and a new resource scientist was hired in mid-2014, reinstating a 3.0 FTE SRL. The additional personnel proved necessary for updating the structure of services at the FCRF and for allowing the time to interact and educate the end users.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec sec-type="materials|methods" id="s2">
      <title>MATERIALS AND METHODS</title>
      <sec id="s3">
        <title>Phase 1: Conception (5 mo)</title>
        <p>End users were approached to discuss the structure of services at FCRF, and responses were documented. This allowed us to determine the different expectations of the FCRF from a wide user base. The advisory committee, in itself representative of the user base, was consulted on the expectations and presented with the idea of change at a committee meeting. Peer institutions were contacted and operations assessed to identify the current practices in successful SRLs. From this market research, it was determined that independent acquisition of flow cytometry data by the end user was the goal of this change in structure of services. This would allow resource scientists at the FCRF time to discuss experimental design, support instrument optimization and acquisition, assist with analysis, and provide feedback on the experimentation. Other key questions were determined at this stage, including how many end users would we have to train and how to communicate this change effectively to the wider community of UNMC investigators. As a means to encourage independent acquisition on the instruments, independent acquisition was priced lower than assisted acquisition. The 5 mo was a necessary timeframe for this market research at the FCRF. This could have been shortened if staff levels had been 3.0 FTEs at the time of conception.</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="s4">
        <title>Phase 2: Design (3 mo)</title>
        <p>To transition from a process where core staff acquired data to one in which end users independently acquired flow cytometry data, 4 key steps of change were identified: 1) end-user education; 2) access to instrument schedules; 3) instrument training; and 4) access to analysis software. Validation steps were deemed necessary to ensure the smooth transition of training large volumes of users. Communication streams were outlined to advertise the change effectively in structure of services at the FCRF. These validation steps would guide the development of new Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) and policies at the FCRF, outlining how the new services would be offered and what steps would be necessary to ensure that correct procedures were followed.</p>
        <p>A date was identified (June 2, 2014) for completion of the validation steps and transition to this new, independent acquisition process. This allowed 10 wk for the transition. Multiple methods were identified for how this change in structure of service would be communicated, including presentations, targeted emails, and personal communication. Based on the number of individual laboratories and average number of flow cytometry users within the laboratories, we determined that the maximum number of investigators that the FCRF would have to train during this transition was 250. This was the maximum number of investigators that would have to undertake the 4 steps defined above. Whereas we did not anticipate all 250 investigators needing to be trained immediately, we planned for this possibility.</p>
        <p>Rate calculations were undertaken to determine the true cost of the services. Flow cytometry was previously charged at $38/h. Based on the new rate calculations, we set the cost for independent acquisition at $35/h and increased the cost for assisted acquisition to $55/h. A training fee of $35/h would be added for individuals who trained after the conclusion of the transitional period.</p>
        <p>The 3 mo was a necessary timeframe for design at the initial site at UNMC. If other SRLs were to adopt this approach, successive design times could be shortened significantly.</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="s5">
        <title>Phase 3: Implementation (2.5 mo)</title>
        <p>Throughout phase 2, validation for each of the 4 steps designed were undertaken. All FCRF personnel were involved in developing the educational content and validating analysis software access on core computers. A description of the educational content is provided in <xref ref-type="table" rid="T1">
            <bold>Table 1</bold>
          </xref>. Select end users, who were keen to operate the flow cytometers independently and who used the core often, were invited to validate the access to instrument schedules and pilot the instrument training. Modifications were made to these 4 steps based on feedback from respective testers. SOPs and policies for the new services were developed and documented.
        </p>
