        <p>During these validation steps, a large communication effort was made to advertise the change in structure of services at the FCRF. June 2, 2014 was identified as the start of the 10-wk transitional phase and August 18, 2014 as when the new structure of services and the new service rates would be implemented. The communication effort included 3 short presentations, delivered once in June, once in July, and again in August. FCRF personnel discussed the change, answered questions, and tried to allay investigators&#x02019; concerns. E-mails were sent describing the changes in structure of service and cost and the key dates for when these would be implemented, as well as highlighting when presentations would occur. These e-mails were sent beginning in May to all research personnel and additionally, to all identified end users of the FCRF once per month, for 3 mo. The e-mails were staggered between all personnel and targeted end users. In addition to e-mails and seminars, FCRF staff actively approached end users as they dropped off samples to discuss the upcoming change in structure of services.</p>
        <p>We made the stated deadlines, and by August 18, 2014, we fully implemented the new structure in services. The 10-wk timeframe was based on availability of staff for end-user training and the number of potential investigators to train. If other SRLs were to adopt this approach, successive implementation times would be dependent on those 2 factors.</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="s6">
        <title>Phase 4: Continued Management (12 mo)</title>
        <p>From August 19, 2014 to August 31, 2015, the FCRF actively monitored the progress of the shift in services, modifying practices to offer more effectively the expertise and instrumentation to end users. An annual survey was sent out to assess the shift in services undertaken, first sent in September 2014.</p>
      </sec>
    </sec>
    <sec sec-type="results" id="s7">
      <title>RESULTS</title>
      <p>The facility monitored attendance of the educational class, which is compulsory for end users who want to achieve independent operation. The second step was training on the Research Support System (RSS), an online, in-house-built scheduling software. The RSS allows end users to view instrument schedules and create/edit/delete appointments up to 24 h in advance of the desired appointment time. The third and final step for approval as an independent operator was the one-on-one instrument training. <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F1">
          <bold>Figure 1</bold>
        </xref> shows the number of end users who attended the educational class, the number who went on to take the RSS training, and the number who completed the one-on-one independent operator training (measured daily during the transition at class intervals for the following 12 mo) and how this relates to the decrease in facility staff-operated analysis over the transition and continued management period.
      </p>
