    <sec sec-type="discussion" id="s8">
      <title>DISCUSSION</title>
      <p>The knowledge of concepts from manufacturing and information technology structure and the application of them to an SRL business strategy facilitated insightful planning and implementation of major changes to the structure of services offered at the FCRF. Through this approach, the FCRF has successfully instilled a culture change in how end users interact with the facility (<xref ref-type="fig" rid="F1">Fig. 1</xref>). During the transition of Phase 3 (June 2&#x02013;August 18, 2014), the percentage of facility staff-operated analysis decreased from 100 to 40%, a substantial shift in how end users interact with the facility. For the past 12 mo, the use has remained hovering at this 40% facility staff-operated analysis level.</p>
      <p>The number of individuals who take the independent, one-on-one training spiked in the days leading up to August 18, 2014 (end of the transition period), after which, a fee was introduced for the one-on-one training. This indicates the fact that the fee structure and the dates for implementing the shift in services were communicated effectively (many people sought to complete training before fees were introduced, and rates for assisted acquisition increased).</p>
      <p>In the 12 mo following, there has been a steady and continual attendance for the educational class that correlates strongly with the number of individuals taking the RSS and further one-on-one instrument training (<xref ref-type="fig" rid="F1">Fig. 1</xref>). Patterns in attendance at the class will be used to identify whether additional classes are warranted; for example, when a new term starts, and there is an influx of new students. At these peak demand months, as part of Phase 4 (continued management), we may seek to increase capacity for training by offering 2 classes per month as opposed to the 1 class per month currently offered.</p>
      <p>There is a 12% increase in revenue at the FCRF for fiscal year (FY) 2015 (data not shown), but this is positively and negatively skewed by the reduction in price for independent operation and the increase in price for assisted operation, respectively. Perhaps a better metric for evaluating the impact of the change in structure of services is to compare the year-on-year difference in use. The facility was &#x000b1;5% change in analysis use from 2010 through to 2014. With implementation of independent acquisition in August 2014, there is a 16.5% increase in FY2015 analysis use. This is a direct, immediate, and measurable positive impact from modifying the structure of services at the FCRF (<xref ref-type="fig" rid="F2">Fig. 2</xref>).</p>
      <p>
        <xref ref-type="fig" rid="F3">Figure 3</xref> gives an insight into how the shift in services was perceived during conception and implementation and helps us identify future needs for monitoring and increasing end-user satisfaction. It can be seen from question 1, the change in services was well communicated, with &#x0003e;98% of respondents giving a positive &#x0201c;yes&#x0201d; or &#x0201c;to some extent&#x0201d; answer. Based on communication with the other 2%, we identified alternative lines of communication that may have allowed us to capture the few individuals who did not anticipate the upcoming changes at the FCRF (<italic>e.g.</italic>, a poster on the SRL entrance door). Overall, responses to the survey questions were overwhelmingly positive, indicating that the changes to the FCRF services were well implemented and well received at UNMC.
      </p>
      <p>Throughout the continued management phase, there have been significant improvements in areas of concern that initiated the change in services. Based on responses from end users, the quality of research has increased, with staff being able to spend more time collaborating with researchers and discussing data analysis and interpretation. In addition to staff being named as authors on selected publications, we have documented an increase in FCRF acknowledgments in publications, from a historic cap of 32/yr to 48 FCRF acknowledgments in FY2015. At least anecdotally, facility staff morale has improved as stress and work hours have been reduced.</p>
      <p>The 4 phases adapted from product lifecycle management were effective in the realization of what changes were necessary, for defining the steps needed to achieve these changes and identifying necessary validation steps, for delivering this change effectively to the end users at UNMC, and for monitoring and maintaining the structure of services at the FCRF. If such disruptive changes are necessary, then this adaptation of product lifecycle management has proven to be a valuable resource in SRL business and operations management.</p>
      <p>As a result of the positive outcomes that we have seen at UNMC FCRF, we are investigating the use of this adapted product lifecycle management approach to make similar improvements at another flow cytometry SRL located at another institute. Whereas each SRL will differ in the specifics, this 4-phase approach has been demonstrated to work well for identifying improvements in value and in providing a process for SRLs to become successful partners for biomedical research. This approach should be considered by all SRL management when faced with the need for operationally disruptive measures.</p>
      <sec id="s9">
        <title>Product Lifecycle Management</title>
        <p>Product lifecycle management is a strategy to resolve effectively problems of designing and introducing a new product and supporting that product throughout its lifetime. This includes technology, processes, and best practices to develop a solution to business problems. Through product lifecycle management, a business can transform products and processes to enhance performance and increase the value of the product for both customers and shareholders. Three of the lifecycle phases (idea, definition, and realization) make up the Beginning of Life. The Middle of Life includes supporting the product during use. At the end of the useful lifespan of the product comes the End of Life, where the product is retired and/or eliminated.<xref rid="B2" ref-type="bibr">
            <sup>2</sup>
          </xref> Different individuals can be responsible for the product during these different stages. Product lifecycle management strategies support implementing these stages by defining how people, processes, and information will be integrated.<xref rid="B3" ref-type="bibr">
            <sup>3</sup>
          </xref>
        </p>
      </sec>
    </sec>
